I had it with me too
sometimes, like if there's

00:48:16.170 --> 00:48:18.812
a situation when you get
upset, whip out the book.

00:48:18.812 --> 00:48:21.020
RONA RENNER: Well, if you
ever want to send it to me,

00:48:21.020 --> 00:48:22.445
I'll post it on my website.

00:48:22.445 --> 00:48:25.510
Oh by the way,
nurserona.com is my website.

00:48:25.510 --> 00:48:26.570
I should say that.

00:48:26.570 --> 00:48:28.560
And I'm also on Google Helpouts.

00:48:28.560 --> 00:48:32.030
OK, let's see-- and
NurseRonaRN Facebook.

00:48:32.030 --> 00:48:34.440
OK, what specific
strategies can you

00:48:34.440 --> 00:48:38.290
offer to deal with young
siblings hitting each other?

00:48:38.290 --> 00:48:40.650
My wife and I try
so many things.

00:48:40.650 --> 00:48:42.620
We want them to work
things out on their own

00:48:42.620 --> 00:48:44.840
without maiming each other.

00:48:44.840 --> 00:48:46.280
Good goal, right?

00:48:46.280 --> 00:48:48.450
No maiming.

00:48:48.450 --> 00:48:51.920
Hitting is coming up a
lot for me in my practice.

00:48:51.920 --> 00:48:53.960
A lot of parents
have been calling me

00:48:53.960 --> 00:48:56.060
because the kids are hitting.

00:48:56.060 --> 00:48:58.360
And I think it's the
kind of thing you really

00:48:58.360 --> 00:49:01.720
have to have a serious
family meeting about

00:49:01.720 --> 00:49:05.630
and really set that rule--
no hitting in our house.

00:49:05.630 --> 00:49:10.090
And a lot of parents,
80% of parents

00:49:10.090 --> 00:49:12.530
still use corporal
punishment I'm told.

00:49:12.530 --> 00:49:15.460
But a lot of parents
use yelling instead of

00:49:15.460 --> 00:49:19.680
hitting, because hitting
was seen to not be so good.

00:49:19.680 --> 00:49:22.670
But if you can say no
hitting in our household,

00:49:22.670 --> 00:49:26.200
because you don't use that
yourself, it's a good way

00:49:26.200 --> 00:49:29.020
to have a meeting
and say, hitting

00:49:29.020 --> 00:49:30.800
is not allowed in this house.

00:49:30.800 --> 00:49:32.190
And here's why.

00:49:32.190 --> 00:49:34.460
I don't want to hit you.

00:49:34.460 --> 00:49:36.400
I don't want you
to hit each other.

00:49:36.400 --> 00:49:40.580
Those kids, the person who
sent this, thank you very much.

00:49:40.580 --> 00:49:43.490
They also need one-on-one
time with each parent

00:49:43.490 --> 00:49:45.350
so they're getting
some special attention,

00:49:45.350 --> 00:49:48.390
because that reduces
sibling rivalry.

00:49:48.390 --> 00:49:50.230
And then you might
have to have it

00:49:50.230 --> 00:49:53.350
connected to some
privilege they have.

00:49:53.350 --> 00:49:55.000
And I do say that
once in a while,

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:57.340
you need to do that
to break a habit.

00:49:57.340 --> 00:50:01.490
And it might be that they love
their TV time after dinner.

00:50:01.490 --> 00:50:04.394
And it may be that here's
this very simple chart,

00:50:04.394 --> 00:50:05.560
you didn't hit your brother.

00:50:05.560 --> 00:50:08.980
There was no maiming today.

00:50:08.980 --> 00:50:11.040
You each get your TV time.

00:50:11.040 --> 00:50:14.140
And if hitting happens, you
won't, because in our house

00:50:14.140 --> 00:50:16.830
there's privilege
and responsibility.

00:50:16.830 --> 00:50:19.670
Kids think that the TV
or the iPhone or the pad

00:50:19.670 --> 00:50:21.170
is attached to them.

00:50:21.170 --> 00:50:23.310
They think it's another
organ sometimes,

00:50:23.310 --> 00:50:24.980
especially with older kids.

00:50:24.980 --> 00:50:27.460
And we have to remember
that those are privileges.

00:50:27.460 --> 00:50:30.410
So sometimes you need
a little leverage.

00:50:30.410 --> 00:50:33.790
But I think the first step is to
really have that family meeting

00:50:33.790 --> 00:50:36.920
and say, this is
important to us.

00:50:36.920 --> 00:50:40.350
We really don't want anyone
in our house to get hit.

00:50:40.350 --> 00:50:42.570
I can take another question.

00:50:42.570 --> 00:50:45.840
AUDIENCE: Can you suggest any
simple conversational tactics

00:50:45.840 --> 00:50:49.560
for suggesting your book to
someone who could probably

00:50:49.560 --> 00:50:52.100
use it without seeming
to obviously insult

00:50:52.100 --> 00:50:53.400
their capabilities as a parent?

00:50:53.400 --> 00:50:55.666
Maybe this person is
even married to you,

00:50:55.666 --> 00:50:57.290
or maybe it's a
relative or a stranger.

00:50:57.290 --> 00:50:58.665
RONA RENNER: Right,
just like me.

00:50:58.665 --> 00:50:59.832
I love it, I love it.

00:50:59.832 --> 00:51:01.040
How do you suggest this book?

00:51:01.040 --> 00:51:03.470
And I've had a lot of
people ask me that.

00:51:03.470 --> 00:51:08.650
And in your case, you
just bring it home

00:51:08.650 --> 00:51:11.340
and say, God, I heard this
really good talk at Google

00:51:11.340 --> 00:51:11.950
today.

00:51:11.950 --> 00:51:14.790
And I just thought-- and
then just leave it there.

00:51:14.790 --> 00:51:17.000
But don't say, here honey.

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:19.000
This is for you.

00:51:19.000 --> 00:51:21.980
Because she's not going to
like it, or he or whoever

00:51:21.980 --> 00:51:23.650
it is, not going
to like it so much.

00:51:23.650 --> 00:51:25.890
So you could say,
I got this book.

00:51:25.890 --> 00:51:27.540
I thought that I
could learn a lot.

00:51:27.540 --> 00:51:30.320
And if you're
interested, we might even

00:51:30.320 --> 00:51:33.397
want to look at the
temperament piece together.

00:51:33.397 --> 00:51:35.480
There's a whole chapter
on different temperaments.

00:51:35.480 --> 00:51:39.290
So that's sort of a safe
neutral place to go.

00:51:39.290 --> 00:51:42.790
I've had people ask me
that who are grandparents

00:51:42.790 --> 00:51:45.710
and they want to give the
book to their children who

00:51:45.710 --> 00:51:47.270
are yelling a lot and.

00:51:47.270 --> 00:51:49.910
I think you have to be really
tactful, because no one wants

00:51:49.910 --> 00:51:52.340
to be told they're a bad parent.

00:51:52.340 --> 00:51:55.770
We feel insecure as parents.

00:51:55.770 --> 00:51:59.140
But if you are living with
someone who's yelling a lot,

00:51:59.140 --> 00:52:02.086
you can have that honest
conversation, say you know?

00:52:02.086 --> 00:52:03.950
I know we have different styles.

00:52:03.950 --> 00:52:08.710
You're Italian, I'm not,
whatever you want to say.

00:52:08.710 --> 00:52:10.500
And I know we have
different styles.

00:52:10.500 --> 00:52:12.760
But I thought maybe we
could read this together,

00:52:12.760 --> 00:52:17.750
because the studies are
showing that a lot of yelling

00:52:17.750 --> 00:52:20.100
is detrimental to kids.

00:52:20.100 --> 00:52:23.030
And I know I'm not perfect
and I do things wrong.

00:52:23.030 --> 00:52:28.520
And maybe, maybe you would
yell less if I pitched in more.

00:52:28.520 --> 00:52:31.010
Because that's the other thing
I talk about in the book,

00:52:31.010 --> 00:52:33.050
that sometimes you're
yelling because you

00:52:33.050 --> 00:52:37.150
want your partner to hear that
they need help-- that you need

00:52:37.150 --> 00:52:38.400
help, not that they need help.

00:52:38.400 --> 00:52:41.000
So I'm busy and I'm
yelling at my kids.

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:43.480
But what I really want is my
partner to come in and help.

00:52:43.480 --> 00:52:45.760
So it could open up
a great conversation.

00:52:45.760 --> 00:52:47.720
I think it's 12:59.

00:52:47.720 --> 00:52:48.650
We need to stop.

00:52:48.650 --> 00:52:51.380
And I'll stick around if
anyone has more questions.

00:52:51.380 --> 00:52:53.470
And I'd be happy
to sign your books.

00:52:53.470 --> 00:52:55.230
And I just want to
thank you so much,

00:52:55.230 --> 00:52:58.060
and thank Janice Keyser
for being my host.

00:52:58.060 --> 00:53:01.110
